primitive data types: 8 types

1. logical - boolean
boolean x = true;
boolean y = false;
boolean v = 0; // error 

2. Textual - char 
char c = 'A';
Textual - String (class) --- it is in java.lang 
String s1 = "Hello world"; // pool for memory reduction purpose 
String s2 = "Hello world"; 
String s1 = new String("Bad practice");
String s2 = new String("Bad practice");

3. Integral - byte(1) - 8 bits, short(2) - 16 bits, int(4) - 32 bits, and long(8) - 64 bits
decimal form - 2
octal form - 077
hexadecimal - 0xBAAC
default is int 

4. Floating - double(4) - 32 bits, and float(8) - 64 bits 
3.14 default is double 
3.14F; for floating with suffixing with F
float x = 3.14; // gives an error because it is a double
float x = 3.14F; 

Widenning - converting a lower datatype to a higher datatype this is implicit
char c = 'f';
int v = c; // so ASCII value of f is 70 

Narrowing - converting a higher datatype to a lower datatype this is explicit 
int v = 70;
char c = (char) v; // F which is the ASCII value of 70